The White House chief arrives in the northern Way metropolis tomorrow along with his wife Michelle and will be busy all the time.
First, he pays a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time ever with the five committee members who elected him in October out of 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with the Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He is the fourth U.S. president, but only as the third to accept the prize directly in office.
The White House has already said that Obama will talk about the Afghanistan war when it comes to taking over the prize.
The president doesn't want to dodge this issue because he knows he's taking the award as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque over ten million Swedish crowns (approx. 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The programme of events then envisages a banquet with the president and his wife, which will be attended by the prime minister and another 250 invited guests in addition to Norway's king and queen.
Obama was very reluctant from the start to the price.
He cited, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve the price.
Several times he also reiterated that it is the price not only for him, but for all those who seek the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this is "call to action" for him.
