A change of course in aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "A baby more means a grave more."
These lessons they have learned so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who, due to the low birth rate and the ageing population, suddenly began to change course this summer and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their response was immediate and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There's nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, spoiled single children affectionately called "little emperors," a population crisis in the country is drawing up.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time when this policy came into force, the UN-
Department of Population Issues, while the number of population groups of 60 years and older is expected to increase explosively from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 percent in 2020. This is far above the global average of approx. 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and the elderly accounted for almost 22 percent of Shanghai's reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of procreative age must have babies to "help lower the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the labor shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial injunction introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical strain on natural country's resources could be avoided, whereas human rights advocates have condemned abuses in enforcing policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had gender-selective abortions performed, creating an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policies.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule --- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many tough slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the University of Beijing's Institute of Population Research, said that government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children who are a partner to be an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city government has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the Shanghai outdoor areas said an upswing is evident in the applications of couples who want a second child after the campaign launches, the city districts, by contrast, report no change.
At the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, only four to five applications are received as an example per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the number of births expected in the city expected for 2010 still at about ca. 165,000 will be -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
