But they, like many Chinese, own only a minor government health and life insurance policy.
Without a social network, they say, that decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West falsely rate the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, we are being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply in a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples state psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she only wanted a child because she was an only child, too. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it more bluntly.
For parents from the middle class with a double career, through which the birth rate decreases, he said, it is about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of 20- to 39-year-olds grew up struggling their parents during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
