Oslo's speech: the "just war" brings Obama praise from the right
The American right on Friday welcomed the speech given by Barack Obama the night before in Oslo and was satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the notion of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, the allocation of the prize to Obama on 9. October had mocked, this time applauded the president's speech, following the example of the former vice-presidential candidate in the 2008 election Sarah Palin.
I liked what he said, Palin explained, the face of the Republican Party's right wing in the daily USA Today, adding that she herself had raised the subject of a "sometimes necessary" war in her just-published memoirs.
The war is, of course, the last thing I think Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop the terrorists down there, she says.
Obama, the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush has inherited, the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, on Thursday in Oslo sought to justify the use of force; a way of declaring his decision of nine days ago to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, took the view that the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, rejoiced the former president of the House of Representatives, who particularly acknowledged the reference to "the existence of evil in the world" in Obama's words.
In some parts, this speech was considered entirely historic, explained Ginrich, who was interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway."
The previous lawmaker, who is seen by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen a "president of the left" who reminded members of the Nobel Committee that they were "not free and could not hand out a prize for peace if the use of force did not exist."
For Michael Gerson, former writer of George W. Bush, and now editor at The Washington Post, has given Obama "a very American speech."
In addition to portraying himself as a "cosmopolitan," as "he always does," he has "spoken like an American president" when he pointed out that the Europeans "live like in a security bubble that they did not create themselves and for whose protection they don't do much," according to Gerson.
