Long-distance drivers: Three marathons for a deal that secures supply for Christmas
After a three-week negotiating marathon, the unions of the road association and the TLF - the only employers' organization that remained until the end - came to an agreement on Friday evening, which puts an end to the strike order and the looming heavy supply shortage at Christmas.
At the signature meeting on Friday evening, Secretary of State for Transport Dominique Bussereau "welcomed" the agreement, which was initiated on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators separated early Friday morning in the hope of quickly signing the agreement in the late morning.
And this despite the fact that the three employers’ associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting.
However, more than six hours passed from the start of the meeting at 11:00 a.m. until the conclusion of the agreement and the agreement was not signed until 18:00.
The conflict "would have done a lot of damage to the companies" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year," according to Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% wage increase for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages thus rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
"That's not much, but we're starting small," says Patrice Clos (FO).
The activists are now instructed to stop blocking the supply centres.
"However, there will probably always be some recalcitrants who are not satisfied with the settlement," he adds.
TLF chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement," although it was "difficult to admit these wage increases in the face of international competition."
According to him, the increase is 170 euros per month for the low and 100 to 120 euros for the high wage groups.
"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for the workers," said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "a historic agreement."
Richard Jaubert (CGT) commented on this about "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for the increase in travel costs by 3% and the maintenance of the total trade in road transport in the first half of 2010, which will make it possible, in particular, to be addressed 13. To address monthly salary and the modernisation of collective agreements.
M. Bussereau recalled that "the fall in taxes on employers in the amount of 100 million euros" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the draft law of the corrected finances for 2009, which was passed by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government is calling for "an identical" vote from the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows the agreement to apply first to the companies affiliated to this organization and that it will subsequently apply to the entire profession in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
This will be the case "in no time," Bussereau assures.
The opposition of employers' associations can only delay the procedure.
The FNTR association denounced a "fraudulent trade" because the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax."
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as soon as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but in order not to kill the goose eaters on the approaching Christmas days, the Unostra laments.
For the association Otre, the agreement threatens to "shovel a large grave for small and medium-sized companies in the industry in the next 12 months."
