Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday announced the dissolution of the country's pro-Kurdish main party; a decision that immediately followed angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the country's southeast and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government enormously more difficult, which is striving to extend the hand of the Kurdish community to put an end to the conflicts that have lasted for 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "site for activities that are detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the Hasim Kiliç Constitutional Court told the press four days after the decision.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes required to impose the dissolution. He also pointed out that 37 of the party's leaders, including Chairman Ahmet Türk and Parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political events for a period of five years.
Furthermore, the judge announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity that Türk and Tugluk enjoy, as well as the confiscation of the party's goods.
The DTP now has 21 seats in parliament (out of 550).
The party leaders expressed themselves before the verdict that the parliamentarians would rather leave the parliament than meet like non-party parliamentarians.
The decision followed proceedings initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court of Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "instructions" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which is seen by Ankara and numerous other countries as a terrorist organization.
Numerous observers are of the view that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has "no connection" to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The ruling of the Constitutional Court sparks the government in between, which seeks to accommodate the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds in order to let the support of the PKK by the Kurds dry up and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP reaffirm that a dissolution could lead to a re-eruption of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan had led to clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the premises of the DTP in the multimillion-dollar city of Diyarbakir in the southeast, which is predominantly populated by Kurds.
Law enforcement deployed tear gas grenades and water cannons as the protesters began throwing Molotov cocktails and rocks.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision will "deepen the despair even further."
"Turkey can do this (Kurdish, ed. Editorial) Question not to clarify on the basis of the prohibition of a party," he explained to the press.
The government, made up of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closure of the parties on principle.
That doesn't solve the problems," according to Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedoing of the democratic opening that has been promoted by the government," according to political market observer Ahmet Insel.
"You can obviously prepare for a reaction from the PKK," he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey three days earlier. This was one of the most brutal attacks of the past few months.
