The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-tall animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
Yet Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body traits, report Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea at the equator at the time.
Tawa is opening a new window for the early evolution of the dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
He shows us much about the kinship relations, the spread and the features of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began a dig at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones the researchers quickly identified as a new species.
Over the course of the excavation, they gathered the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the Sun God of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it's an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually you only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primal dinosaurs is usually controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three most important lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long necks" and their relatives, and the plant-eating Ornithischa (bird basin dinosaurs), for example
After analyzing Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three lines of development separated early on and spread from South America across all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as supercontinent Pangaea.
This is supported by the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot derive from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could emerge, because in South America, a particularly large number of primitive dino fossils have simply been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant land vertebrae of the Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying dinosaurs and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the kinship on the border from the Triassic to the Jurassic died out.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
