Some see images in an alert state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and in the drug frenzy, the boundaries between imagination and reality blur.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark rooms, we are allowed to indulge in the wildest ideas and fantasy images uninhibited.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in wakefulness, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or addicted to drugs in the modern Western world, at least as a strange.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the case of the mentally ill or in the drug frenzy.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make sure that the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Dream-like changed waking consciousness states can occur in a variety of forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Even if the trigger and effect may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapturizing states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the brain's neural messengers - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - derails and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very frequently during schizophrenic psychosis.
