Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted faces, teeth-scrambling.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar out of walls and radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. tears two cables from the stereo, knots them into a sling and attaches them to a hook to the ceiling.
He climbs on a loudspeaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The sling is loosening.
This is supposed to be a lesson to you, shouting the voices in drum fur-tight choir, "go to the clinic and let yourself heal!"
Today is Henning T. 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one is 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoffective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medication, for depression, the mania, the schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The mirages are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in a lifetime, in psychiatric hospitals it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution delusions.
Especially common is listening to voices - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not rare.
The sufferer is unable to separate important things from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded by impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
Reality perception in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he becomes, similar to the dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality comparison is usually not possible for them, the mirages are cruel reality, waking up excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in the dream, says Fuchs, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality perceived in psychosis is basically preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of experience takes place in the real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
States of emergency can cause anyone to briefly lose their reality, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the trigger for psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychoses because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are running hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether mirages are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and illusions for ten years, last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Unreal World in Our Minds".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychoses, but also of an astonishing number of other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often also include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and traumatic brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They occur when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brains are running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulus deprivation, stress, lovesickness or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said they had experienced hallucination at least once in their lifetime.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During the break, it can happen that a lanky boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she wonders sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other mirages are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually scary
Often the mirages are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears just introduces a new classmate, while he explains mathematical equations for everyone else, as he hears and visibly on the board.
At night, the appearances are usually scary.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming whether the pictures she sees, the faces or the girl with the bleeding lacerations on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she'll yell at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell them about it, they would think they're crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed the high school diploma last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she made contact with the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows full well that she is not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus deprivation, they are likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then underemployed and provides for its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls dad since she can think is not her biological father.
Since the same areas of the brain are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to distinguish between mirages and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is reflected there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, so they look so real."
Even nightly dream pictures, Kasten sees as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are no different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their mirages as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to value the hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
In our too much-minded world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains positives, creative - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of trauma-like changed waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking condition even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in traumatic or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients, who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by self- and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation is not possible in reality, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is presented in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning-making and meaning in a situation that is unbearable in itself, which enables us people to have their own creative ability not to perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue operation of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after heart valve surgery with subsequent heart transplant, while his body is condemned to lack of movement in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make intoxicants from blood.
Is abducted by a Greek on a motorcycle in his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes completely up in the imagined happening, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travel are still clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience transcends the horizons of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug frenzy show how brittle our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist sums up box, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
