75% of working mothers have experienced problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the job market limited due to their motherhood.
The study discloses that there are vast differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of profession they are practicing.
Those of them who do not do another job outside the house, only work half-day or do not have a fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"The women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a permanent employment get their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving in together, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have come together and who have only realized the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to receive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they have only the secondary school leaving certificate or a higher education, became mother for the first time, on average, with 25.1 or 32.1.
Furthermore, depending on their level of education, there is another difference between women.
While the women with a main degree marry before their first permanent position and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree make it the other way around and first find a permanent position and marry after it and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
