Michelin and Fesvial together for the use of the helmet
The tyre manufacturer Michelin, in cooperation with the Spanish Foundation for Road Safety (Fesvial), has launched a campaign to promote helmet use, especially among the younger motorcyclists, as both companies announced today.
This initiative aims to draw attention to the importance of helmet use, since this is ultimately the only protective element that can prevent head injuries or even death in the event of a motorcycle accident.
Michelin pointed out that this campaign is part of its commitment to road safety, which "involves far more than just the design and manufacture of products that are becoming safer and safer with each passing day" and further affirmed that, even with other actions of educational and informative character, they are helping to get one step closer to this goal every day.
This new campaign to promote helmet use on the motorcycle, which runs under the slogan 'To be or not to be', will distribute posters to over 500 motorcycle workshops in a first phase to achieve the best possible distribution.
In conclusion, Michelin emphasized that road safety is "a constant concern" of the company, and precisely for the reason that, as a manufacturer of tires for two-wheeled vehicles, it is always committed to the fact that one of its main goals must be the development of increasingly safe products.
The sale of small trucks is rising again
After almost two years, the car market for vans is finally beginning to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% in relation to 2008, and, more importantly, they are thus the first increase ever after 22 consecutive months with a steady decline, according to the figures presented by the manufacturers association Anfac and the car dealer association Ganvam.
However, these good figures are currently only to be enjoyed with great caution, since the reference data used for comparison are of November 2008, which was a particularly poor year of sale with a decrease of 60% in respect of the previous year.
However, it must be borne in mind that, apart from the increase in the last month, the total approvals of these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures of the previous financial year.
Since January, a total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold, but this figure includes all vehicles that make up the van market: descendants of passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, small vans and lighter small trucks/cars.
Furthermore, the same thunderclouds in the sky that affect the demand most are still, because even if some of the vehicles are bought by private individuals, the majority of sales go to small and medium-sized enterprises, which make the purchase with third-party financing in almost 100% of all cases.
Thus, with these restrictions, which are the result of the turned-on money tap of the credit institutions, one must include other factors, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
With this panorama and in contrast to the passenger cars, the financial support in the purchase of a vehicle of the 2000E plan has helped little.
However, this plan is not only intended for private individuals, even self-employed and small companies have a right to buy a van up to 3.5 tons with a CO2 emission, which may not exceed 160 grams per kilometer driven, but the low sales figures speak for themselves.
Just yesterday, Ganvam had reminded that it is absolutely necessary on the part of the state to also pay special attention to these small trucks as well as, of course, to the industrial vehicles (lorry and bus).
The car dealers association predicts a similar year for 2010 as the previous year, for which it expects a sales failure (in the case of passenger cars and SUVs) of 19%.
Support in braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS and how it is happening now with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in the European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a waiting period until the end of February 2011 was set.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end collisions because of their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical braking maneuver, which the system recognizes on the basis of the brake strength on the brake pedal carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even get around to pedaling on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, engages the brake system with maximum force and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that one in four accidents with personal injury could be prevented - once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it would become necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
