Real Madrid and the F.C. Barcelona have benefited from this distribution.
The white club is third in Europe, which has earned the most money through its participation and, alongside AC Milan, the only one that has won the trophy three times.
The reigning Catalan champion and last winner of the former 1992 European Cup finishes fifth.
The list is tops Manchester United and Bayern Munich, two teams that also raised the most money through their participation in the past Champions League.
Even though they lost to Barça.
On the other hand, Spain is only in third place among the countries that could take money through the champions, although it has more titles than all the others (five, unlike four in Italy, three at England and two at Germany).
Distribution
This obvious contradiction is explained by the complicated cash allocation procedure that UEFA applies.
In this fiscal year, the organization, whose chairman Michel Platini holds, expects revenues of 1,090 million from the Champions League.
Of this money, UEFA envisages 413.1 million for fixed payments: each of the 20 football clubs that took part in the qualifying preliminary round (among them the Atlético de Madrid) received 2.1 million.
In addition, those who won a participation got 3.8 million through their blous presence, in addition to the 550,000 euros for each game they played.
There is also a bonus for winning (800,000 euros) and for a draw (400,000 per team). The clubs that have reached the eighth final will each receive three million; the four who have reached the quarter-finals, 3.3 million.
The last four will each get 4 million.
The winner earns 9 million, as opposed to the second, which receives 5.2 million.
For example, a football club receives at least 7.1 million and a maximum of 31.2 million in fixed revenues.
Barça, in turn, earned 2.5 million with his victory at the European Super Cup in August.
However, there are also variable payments for which 337.8 million are earmarked.
This money is allocated proportionally to the value of each individual television market.
