CNMV approves Paternina's public invitation to issue a public invitation to issue by the investment company Mer
The National Stock Exchange Commission (CNMV) approved the public invitation to tender for Federico Paternina submitted by the investment company Mer on the past 9. October.
The supervisory authority stated that it approved this invitation to tender after it had been proven that the conditions adhere to the final laws and thus the content of the presented explanatory supplement, after the amendments of the previous 2. December, can be considered "sufficient."
CNMV has also announced that this offer is aimed at the acquisition of 550,008 shares of Federico Paternina at the price of 7.65 euros per share, which in turn is 8.95% of the share capital, which is made up of 6,142,786 euros in shares authorised on the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
Furthermore, it was also informed that 5,592,778 million shares have been fixed, which can not be transferred in any way until the tender is completed and whose price has been fixed by Federico Paternina in accordance with the final laws.
New vehicle assessment programmes
In these days of severe weather and accidents, not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage incurred and the cost of the repair.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including the parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of the reviewers use these types of systems.
The service and application providers for the evaluation of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to work on them afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reports are prepared with their products.
The other two companies competing in the tool market for review and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers work together, with each of them providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is becoming ever larger, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and motorizations have come on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
Once a new car hits the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a tedious task, because every single of the thousand-thousand-metre vehicle parts must be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, an "intelligent" graphic image is created by each model, on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. At present, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In view of the vehicle fleet travelling on the road, it is more than 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and manufacturing databases, Audatex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each and every one of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the file or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax through a guide who informs about the value of used cars.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products Audatex offers, it’s easy to get an overview of the kind of support it gives to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
Except for the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for, depending on the intended use, i.e. for each expert opinion.
The most expensive it will be for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that produces thousands of expert opinions negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran off the assembly line solely on the basis of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an open service for the specialist market on the Internet, with which you can offer for vehicles that have been declared total damage.
Your statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analysis, or obtaining information about the deviations by make and model.
One can thus examine, for example, how many models of a certain car brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and provides digital images in the same way, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, which in 1971 was developed as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and injuries. Maintenance of vehicles was established.
The GT guide for expert opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased annually in the last three years with 20% and in 2008 the turnover was 10.8 million euros.
Early last year, they began to go on the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of which are in Spain.
Total revenue in the world of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounts to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In Germany, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera group was worth 1 billion dollars on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at a value of 2.4 billion dollars.
Since 2007, they have been on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's reference index.
